{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511153"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:38:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:38:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11704"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11704"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.03,0.51,0.17,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4319"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105673"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4319"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11704"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88124"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"492"},{"type":"tags","id":"937"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5671"},{"type":"tags","id":"11408"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6729"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38181"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105673"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA surgeon is planning to do an elective procedure on an 82-year-old woman. The procedure has been fully discussed with the patient and the surgeon was able to determine that the patient has decision-making capacity and was able to give informed consent for the procedure. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe specialist\u0027s rooms are contacted by the patient\u0027s son, who wants to discuss his mother\u0027s planned case. The son had earlier attended with his mother for her anaesthetics appointment. The anaesthetist has warned the surgeon that the son is demanding, spending much time asking irrelevant questions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate action for the surgeon to take?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange an interview with the son","Arrange to see the son immediately after the procedure","See the son, on the condition he attends together with his mother","See the son, provided he has medical power of attorney","Arrange to see with the son, with a time limit on the interview"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPatient information is confidential and thus a patient must specifically give consent regarding disclosure of their healthcare information (except in specific circumstances such as minors). In this scenario, there is no clear indication that the women has provided consent for her information to be shared with her son. This rules out every option except for \u003Cstrong\u003Eseeing the son with the mother\u003C/strong\u003E. By seeing the two together, it gives the doctor the chance to ask the mother consent to disclose her medical information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt does not make a difference whether the son is seen before or \u003Cstrong\u003Eafter the procedure\u003C/strong\u003E and whether or not there is a \u003Cstrong\u003Etime limit on the interview\u003C/strong\u003E. If there is not consent from the mother then the son should not be privy to her medical information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the son happens to have \u003Cstrong\u003Epower of attorney\u003C/strong\u003E, then this becomes relevant only if the mother lacks capacity. If the mother became incompetent, it would be necessary for the surgeon to disclose her medical information in order to the medical power of attorney to facilitate them in making decisions about her treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIt should be noted that while the son cannot receive any medical information about his mother\u0027s condition without her consent, the son is allowed to provide health information to the surgeon if he believes it is relevant and in his mother\u0027s best interest for this information to be disclosed to her doctor. Should the doctor refuse to receive this information and a bad outcome was to ensue, then this is another issue.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Medical information of a competent patient may only be disclosed with their consent"],"references":["P\u00e9rez-C\u00e1rceles MD, Pere\u00f1iguez JE, Osuna E, Luna A, Mart\u00edn M, Machado F, et al. Balancing confidentiality and the information provided to families of patients in primary care. J Med Ethics. 2005;31(9):531\u2013535. doi: 10.1136/jme.2004.009944. Available at: https://jme.bmj.com/content/31/9/531"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88124"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11704"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88124"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-11T13:29:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-11T13:30:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4319"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105673"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}